<font color="#FF0000">COMMENTS AGAIN</font><br>
<tt>Wed Feb 26 22:55:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To Doc Spatz:<br>
     Thanks for your input on this site.  I may not have always agreed with your views and may not still agree with some, but hearing your side is better than speculating on it.  If I don't use my own identity or e-mail, that is my choice, since as a vet with certain views, I have recieved negative e-mail from cowards who felt fit to insult me personally for my service.  I have gone back over many of the sites talked about on this server, and it does seem your are more open to discuss and different view points now.  In regards to your views then (during the war) and now, I am one person that tolerates people who have a opinion over those that have none.  I may not agree with your opinion, but it is better you have it (and change it as you learn) than no opinion.  Those luke warm poeple who ride the middle of the road are the ones I despise.  Their apathy kept the Vietnam war going for as long as it did.  They had no interest in then and many have a self serving interst now (mostly a vindication of their inaction).  Keep posting Doc Spatz, since open discussion needs to continue. Critical analysis of all facets of our divided generation needs to continue.  I would rather let the chips fall where they may, than let the misconceptions rule. <br>
To Doc Del:  Thanks for coming here too.  It is easy for a vet to share his pain, I've felt the same way I guess.  Our side (the vet) needs to be heard, if not only for us, then for the medics you mentioned or any other guy whose story is untold and opinion unexpressed.  Keep posting and lets keep the discussion going.  It is our job to make sure that others know of the good we did, and not the crap that has been passed off as gospel.    
<p><code>--   (Prophet) </code><p>


